    "notes": "Stellar Phase 2 curated 2026-05-30 under curation-data-contract (Tier 1 inversion fix). Vega is a POLE-ON RAPID ROTATOR (i ~5-6 deg) with strong gravity darkening, so polar and equatorial Teff/R differ substantially and a single value is an approximation. Primary anchor = Monnier et al. 2012 CHARA/MIRC imaging 'Concordance Model' (the most recent revision; argues earlier work overestimated gravity darkening; all values cache-verified from its Table 2): R_polar 2.418 +/- 0.012, R_equatorial 2.726 +/- 0.007 Rsun (recommended radius = equatorial, the larger extent; Phase 3 should treat the star as oblate, mean ~2.6 Rsun); T_polar 10070 +/- 90, T_equatorial 8910 +/- 130, surface-mean Teff 9360 +/- 90 K (recommended); bolometric L 47.2 +/- 2.0 Lsun (apparent, pole-on-inflated, 58.4 +/- 2.2); mass 2.15 (+0.10/-0.15) Msun; age 700 (+150/-75) Myr (rotation-aware Geneva tracks). The four gravity-darkened models disagree: equatorial Teff spans 7557 (Peterson 2006) - 8910 (Monnier); ages 455 Myr (Yoon 2010, non-rotating isochrones) - 700 Myr (Monnier, rotation-aware) -- DOCUMENTED DIVERGENCE, recommend Monnier. Yoon 2010 (no arXiv) alt: mass 2.135, R_pol 2.362/R_eq 2.818, T_pol 10059/T_eq 8152, age 455 Myr. [Fe/H] = -0.5 (lambda Boo surface depletion; Yoon Z ~0.008, Monnier adopts Z 0.006/[Fe/H] -0.5). Rotation P = 0.71 +/- 0.03 d (Petit 2010 spectropolarimetric magnetic detection; Alina 2012; consistent with Monnier v_eq+R), omega/omega_crit ~0.77-0.88, v sin i 22 km/s, v_eq ~195-236 km/s, gravity-darkening beta 0.231. ACTIVITY: log R'HK is NOT physically defined for an A0 V star (no convective dynamo/chromosphere) -- intentionally not recorded; X-ray is a non-detection, L_X < 2e25 erg/s (Pease, Drake & Kashyap 2006, 'the darkest bright star')."
  }
